#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/trace.h.rst:78
msgid "Contexts"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/trace.h.rst:80
msgid ""
"Contexts are a way to tell the tracing API what part of your application is "
"currently running. Contexts are effectively maintained as a stack of current "
"contexts."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/trace.h.rst:84
msgid ""
"A context might be something as big as \"running physics\" or as small as "
"\"updating animations on entity X\"."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/trace.h.rst:87
msgid ""
"The granularity of the context stack is up to the team instrumenting their "
"application. Some applications may find fine-grained contexts more useful, "
"while others are more comfortable with larger contexts."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/trace.h.rst:91
msgid ""
"Rather than getting a stack trace on every tracing call, we can often look "
"at the current context stack and record that instead, which is much cheaper."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/api_reference/trace.h.rst:95
msgid ""
"When contexts are fully implemented by the server, they will also be used to "
"track how much time is spent in each context (a primitive profiling "
"mechanism), as well as how much memory has been allocated and freed while "
"the context was active. This should help give a good idea of which parts of "
"your application are using more memory or creating a lot of churn (and "
"possibly heap fragmentation)."
msgstr ""

